<worksheet label="ws-act-5-3-1">
  <page>
    <activity xml:id="act-5-3-1" workspace="6cm">
      <introduction>
        <p>
      Evaluate each of the following indefinite integrals.
      Check each antiderivative that you find by differentiating.

      </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-5-3-1-task-0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int \sin(8-3x) \, dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Think <m>\int \sin(u) \, du</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m>\int \sin(8-3x) \, dx = -\frac{1}{3} (-\cos(8-3x)) + C</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>u=8-3x</m> is linear and <m>\int \sin(u) \, du = -\cos(u) + C</m>,
            it follows that <m>\int \sin(8-3x) \, dx = -\frac{1}{3} (-\cos(8-3x)) + C</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-5-3-1-task-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int \sec^2 (4x) \, dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Think <m>\int \sec^2 (u) \, du</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m>\int \sec^2 (4x) \, dx = \frac{1}{4} \tan(4x) + C</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>4x</m> is linear and <m>\int \sec^2(u) \, du = \tan(u) + C </m>,
            we see <m>\int \sec^2 (4x) \, dx = \frac{1}{4} \tan(4x) + C</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="6.5cm" xml:id="act-5-3-1-task-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int \frac{1}{11x - 9} \, dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Think <m>\int \frac{1}{u}\, du</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m>\int \frac{1}{11x - 9} \, dx = \frac{1}{11} \ln|11x - 9| + C</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Using the fact (from <xref ref="Ez-4-4-antid-of-1-over-x">Exercise</xref>) that <m>\int \frac{1}{u} \, du = \ln |u| + C</m>,
            we have <m>\int \frac{1}{11x - 9} \, dx = \frac{1}{11} \ln|11x - 9| + C</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-5-3-1-task-3">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int \csc(2x+1) \cot(2x+1) \, dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Think <m>\int \csc(u) \cot(u) \, du</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m>\int \csc(2x+1) \cot(2x+1) \, dx = -\frac{1}{2}\csc(2x+1) + C</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We know <m>\int \csc(u) \cot(u) \, du = -\csc(u) + C</m>,
            so <m>\int \csc(2x+1) \cot(2x+1) \, dx = -\frac{1}{2}\csc(2x+1) + C</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-5-3-1-task-4">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-16x^2}}\, dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Think <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-u^2}} \, du</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-16x^2}}\, dx = \frac{1}{4} \arcsin(4x) + C</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Observe that <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-u^2}}\, dx = \arcsin(u) + C</m>,
            and thus viewing <m>16x^2 = (4x)^2</m>,
            we see that <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-16x^2}}\, dx = \frac{1}{4} \arcsin(4x) + C</m></p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="6cm" xml:id="act-5-3-1-task-5">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\int 5^{-x}\, dx</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Think <m>\int 5^{u} \, du</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m>\int 5^{-x}\, dx = -\frac{1}{\ln(5)}5^{-x} + C</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>\int 5^{u}\, du = \frac{1}{\ln(5)}5^u + C</m>,
            we have that <m>\int 5^{-x}\, dx = -\frac{1}{\ln(5)}5^{-x} + C</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </page>
</worksheet>
